node.text:
Update: Follow up appointment at the vet today went well. No more symptoms, appetite back, sounds, feels, looks good! 👍
She’s back to her old self in every way, even the tortitude... she was peeved at me here because she still has 2 more days of antibiotics which I have to give her (she HATES it) & has just gotten tonight’s dose. It’s ok though, she’s quick to forgive. 😻
Thanks again for all the love! ❤️❤️

node.title: Goodbye URI & quarantine, hello freedom and feeling good again!

node.text:
Update: I meant to post this last night. It’s been a long week (few weeks if we factor in Tater Tot’s emergency vet visits) with some pretty rough days. I didn’t want to post an update til I had a happy one so here you go! (Sound on) 😺😺
Thank you to everyone who has been asking about her, via comments, DMs, & sending well wishes. Your thoughtfulness has really helped keep my spirits up through this. ❤️
She’s still quarantined in the recovery suite (aka my
bedroom) but as of today her vet said she can join the whole household again! 😺🙌🤗
Now, time to completely clean, sanitize, & disinfect the “recovery suite” before anyone is allowed in. I’m very grateful nobody else got sick and we were able to keep it contained. 
Have a great Saturday everyone! I’ll be cleaning for the rest of the day, and probably night too. 😂😂Much love to you all, Christina (HuMom)

node.text:
Sneezing might sound cute but it can be the first indication of something more serious. Sneezing should never be dismissed for seasonal allergies or environmental irritant especially if it’s frequent & lasts more than a day. This was in the middle of the night after Thanksgiving cleanup when everyone else was in bed. Venus had sneezed a couple times throughout the day but with all the chaos & her appetite being normal we did exactly that..dismissed it for some type of irritant with all the cooking & cleaning. We know a lot but certainly make mistakes & miss things too so it’s important for us to show humility & share those with you for awareness. 
Our last post shows me doing an analysis to check the color of her gums, eyes, nose, reaction to trying to provoke play, & the color/condition of her eyes. I knew from that little assessment something was off & checking her food bowl (another thing to always be aware of), confirmed it. Her appetite was down too & she felt warm. So, in the very early morning hours of Black Friday I took her to the after hours emergency center Tater Tot @totally_tater was just at last week with obstipation. It was confirmed that she had a fever & was likely suffering from a URI (upper respiratory infection). Our best guess is Tater brought home a “souvenir” even though he isn’t symptomatic. URIs are extremely contagious & Venus missed him so much she ran right to him &  probably groomed him. 
She is improving with the help of being in our bathroom with a humidifier and an antibiotic due to elevated WBC. She’s also quarantined so we can try to avoid cross contamination to the other cats. 
When caught & treated early this is usually not serious but it can be. Always be in tune with what is & isn’t normal with your pets & make sure to seek medical attention if something seems off. You can never be too careful as cats are masters at disguising discomfort & pain. Thankfully, she couldn’t disguise the sneezing. Because of that, she’s being treated & should be good as new in no time! 
I hope this was helpful. Feel free to add anything I missed in comments & please read comments for information others may share. 
Stay well everyone! ❤️

Test your knowledge... Can anyone tell me what it is Mom is assessing here? If you don’t know, read the comments below for awareness because I think most people will know....especially vets, lvts, & anyone in rescue. The 1:30 mark is a very important clue and it was actually very light compared to the next video. 
See next post for the answer, an important message, & to find out where we went while lots of others were out grabbing early morning Black Friday deals. Hint...we weren’t shopping! 🤒

node.text:
Update: 😺😺 I just got word from @thecatfeco  that Sugar is home!!! I don’t know any details other than that but if they choose to divulge more info they don’t mind being shared I’ll update again. Thanks everyone for sharing! 😽

Sharing for @thecatfeco ⬇️

Sugar is missing! A little after 1 pm today,  we have been unable to find Sugar. As all our kitties,  she is very special to us and we want her found as soon as possible. If you see her,  please return her to the Catfe or call us at 7702060971. 

We've contacted the authorities and are reviewing the camera footage. We believe she was stolen. 

Please share this to get the information out and so we can get her back.  That's the most important thing to us. 

#thecatfe #gwinnett #lawrenceville #missingcat

🎉 It’s my 12th birthday! 🎉 
Since we don’t know exactly which day in July I was born, we choose which day to celebrate each year. Since today is the 12th and I’m turning 12, I decided that would be today! I think I’ll keep this theme going each year with celebrating on the day that matches the age I’m turning. 1️⃣2️⃣
Happy birthday to all my fellow July b-day friends! 💗💗
#happybirthday #birthdaygirl #catsofinstagram #weeklyfluff

node.text:
😺 Good news update! 😺
Sorry it’s coming a couple days late but I had some unexpected family matters to take care of Monday after Ginger’s appt that continued into yesterday.
Overall she is improving and we’re seeing more activity out of her as far as exploring around the house more and even jumping up on the couch to join us for the first time in a long time Sunday evening (see all pics)! 🧡So we’ll go over each condition below:
Corneal ulcer- gone! Now we can switch to prednisolone ophthalmology drops to aid in the hypertension that is thought to be at the root of the retinal detachment & hemorrhage.
Secondary glaucoma- pressures have been even at 14 in each eye without pressure drops since she left UGA so this doesn’t seem to be an issue.
Hypertension- her blood pressure looks great & has been checked 2x since leaving UGA. She will remain on her hypertension meds permanently. 
Laryngeal paralysis- this is episodic still (triggered by happy purrs) so we’re trying to focus on ways to stop or shorten the episodes when they happen vs another invasive surgery (laryngeal tie back) which is risky especially at her age & has serious potential post surgical complications which we don’t want to risk if it can be managed based on the complications she suffered from the VBO surgery. Everything on her diagnostic list is thought to be secondary to the surgery or the stress/discomfort of the ear issues prior to surgery. This is definitely a “lesser of two evils” decision which we will continue to monitor & weigh out. 
Kidney disease stage 1- this will continue to be monitored. Her past bloodwork even as of February showed no signs of kidney disease so this is something that we’ll have to re-check at her next visit. Her litter box outputs are normal & healthy so that’s a good sign.
Now, we remain optimistic that she will continue to improve especially since it seems she can hear & see better than the week before and is noticeably more comfortable & happy. 
We’ll see her vet in 2 weeks & will keep everyone posted! Thanks again for all the love & support! 🧡🧡
